	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)">3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> <hi rend="indent(2)"><date>Aug 37</date></hi></p>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> <hi rend="indent(1)"><date>Ab 22nd 5597</date></hi></p>
				<p>&#40;<date>Aug. 23&#44; 1837</date>&#41;</p>
				<p><addressee>Lewis Allen Esq.</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Parnass K.K.M.I.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir&#58;</p>
				<p>Understanding that the <persName>Rev. Jacques Judah Lyons</persName>. Hazan<lb/> of a Congregation of Israelites in <placeName>Paramaribo&#44; <sic>Surinan</sic> Dutch<lb/> Guiana&#44; South America</placeName>&#44; is desirous of reading the Prayers<lb/> for an entire <date>Sabbath</date>&#44; and you having submitted to my inspec&#45;<lb/>tion his credentials&#44; which prove that he has been Hazan for<lb/> a space of five years&#44; and that his conduct has uniformly<lb/> been religious&#58; I yield cheerfully to him the right of so<lb/> reading the entire service&#44; I doing this however <sic>however</sic> I<lb/> utterly disclaim the power of the congregation&#44; unless by a<lb/> majority in meeting <sic>ssembled</sic> of compelling the Hazan for the<lb/> time being&#44; to admit any other person to officiate upon any<lb/> occasion&#44; or for any purpose whatever&#44; by yielding the right<lb/> of the Tebah to him is owing a mere spirit of courtesy&#44; as<lb/> I could not well refuse one who has been in office&#44; to read<lb/> the service&#44; if he is earnestly desirous to do so&#59; although I<lb/> must at the same time express my surprise at the unusual re&#45;<lb/>quest&#44; especially as no communication whatever from the appli&#45;<lb/>cant himself has up to this moment reached me. In conversa&#45;<lb/>tion with Sundry persons I express myself before <persName>Mr. Lyons</persName><lb/> arrival&#44; that if he had been Hazan&#44; I would permit him to<lb/> read&#59; I trust therefore that my compliance with the Revd.<lb/> gentleman&#39;s implied wishes may not be ascribed to motives<lb/> which I do not entertain.</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">Yours respectfully</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)">&#40;over&#41;<persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName></p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>This follows signature</p>
				<p>This note is not private&#44; you may therefore show it to<lb/> any one you please.</p>
				<p>Addr. <addressee>Lewis Allen Esq.</addressee>&#44; Parnass K.K.M.I <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
				<p>Note &#40;on same page as address&#41;</p>
				<p><persName role="author">Revd I Leeser</persName> <date>22&#47;37 Augt.</date> <placeName>Phila.</placeName></p>
				<p>His permission to let <persName>Revd I Lyons</persName> to say <date>Saturday</date> prayers<lb/> do it out of Courtesy &#38;c. &#38;c.  Can make this public&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Enclosing my reply to the same.</p>
				<p>Dear Sir&#58;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">As you have taken the liberty to address a letter to me<lb/> explaining your motives for allowing the <persName>Revd. I. Lyons</persName> to<lb/> read prayers&#44; which explanation I never asked for I take this<lb/> method to tell you I have neither time nor do I choose to make<lb/> your sentiments known to the Congregation.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">And the next time you address a letter to me I wish<lb/> first to read the contents</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)">I am Yours resp</p>
				<p>To <persName role="author">Revd. I. Leeser</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">&#40;enclosed with the above letter&#41;</p>
		</body>
